{"cursor":"21416","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n'Septimania' (, ; , ; , ) was the western region of the Roman province of Gallia\nNarbonensis that passed under the control of the Visigoths in 462, when\nSeptimania was ceded to their king, Theodoric II. Under the Visigoths it was\nknown as simply 'Gallia' or 'Narbonensis'. It corresponded roughly with the\nmodern French region of Languedoc-Roussillon. It passed briefly to the Emirate\nof CÃ³rdoba in the eighth century before its conquest by the Franks, who by the\nend of the ninth century termed it 'Gothia' or the 'Gothic [[March\n(territory)|March]]' (Marca Gothica).\n\nSeptimania was a march of the Carolingian Empire and then West Francia down to\nthe thirteenth century, though it was culturally and politically separate from\nnorthern France and the central royal government. The region was under the\ninfluence of the Toulousain, Provence, and Catalonia. It was part of the\ncultural and linguistic region named Occitania that was finally brought within\nthe control of the French kings in the early 13th century as a result of the\nAlbigensian Crusade after which it came under French governors. From the end of\nthe thirteenth century it was known as Languedoc and its history is tied up with\nthat of France.\n\nThe name \"Septimania\" may derive from part of the Roman name of the city of\nBÃ©ziers, Colonia Julia Septimanorum Beaterrae, which in turn alludes to the\nsettlement of veterans of the Roman VII Legion in the city. Another possible\nderivation of the name is in reference to the seven cities (civitates) of the\nterritory: BÃ©ziers, Elne, Agde, Narbonne, LodÃ¨ve, Maguelonne, and NÃ®mes.\nSeptimania extended to a line half-way between the Mediterranean and the Garonne\nRiver in the northwest; in the east the RhÃ´ne separated it from Provence; and to\nthe south its boundary was formed by the Pyrenees.\n","linknr":385,"url":"Septimania","recorded":1374521441,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Septim